1 About

We have 37K (clean and long) local ancestry segments to test in data coming from African-Americans. These data have some structure due to medical centers and distant genetic relationships (ancestry), explaining a relatively small portion of variance (~5% and ~1%).

In the previous marginal and interaction association scans, we used linear models that ignore variance components and provide fast computation. However, the inflation in test statistics was substantial (1.1-1.2 for marginal and 1.4 for interaction scans). We have applied (unsuccessfully) several modification to linear models to cope with the inflation (QQ-plots on ancestry-based GWAS, Section 2 QQ-plots v0-5 + tunnings):

  • Including an additional random term (1|ccenters) in the framework of Linear Mixed Models (LMMs) slightly reduced the inflation factor from 1.19 to 1.16 (FEV1pp phenotype).
    • The drawback was a slow computation, so we could not apply LMMs to all phenotypes.
  • Including PCs (estimated either from genotypes or ancestry) did not help to fix the problem of inflation.
    • We know that PC1 = global ancestry and the later is presented in the association model, so including PC1 is ambiguous. We also know that PC1 explains the most part of the variance (60%), while the next component PC2 - 3%.

In this report, we will extend the association model one step further by including the genetic random effect. In particular, our analysis has several parts:

  • Figure out the covariance matrix in multivariate normal (MVN) distribution of association test statistics.
    • GARM (includes global ancestry) or ARM (free of global ancestry)?
  • Add the genetic random effect (ancestry), although its contribution to variance is expected to be small.
    • (Zaitlen et al. 2014) showed that 80% heritability estimated using genotypes = 13% heritability estimated using ancestry (Fst = 0.5)
  • Add additional random effect (\(K_d\)) for the interaction analysis (Sul et al. 2016)

We still have other things to implement in the future:

  • Test statistics are still correlated, so we need to implement permutation tests as in (Conneely and Boehnke 2007) and in efficient way.
    • It is a computationally demanding task: 10K permutations, 3K individuals, 37K ancestry segments.

2 GARM or ARM

  • GARM computed on raw ancestry segments data
  • ARM:
    • global ancestry is projected out from ancestry segments data
    • ARM is computed

  • 300 random ancestry long segments selected from Chr 11 and 22
  • we converted covariance to correlation matrices for a fair pair-wise comparison.

2.1 Model of interest

  1. y ~ acs_global + acs_local + (1|sid) with GARM
  2. y ~ acs_global + acs_local + (1|sid) with ARM

As acs_global is PC1 of GARM, the distribution of association statistics is MVN(0, ARM).

We still need to prove this statement in experiments.

3 Model specification

  • We considered only long segments (working on all segments is currently computationally hard)
  • We used ARM (not GARM) as \(K\) matrix in the genetic random effect, because acs_global is a covariate in association models.

3.1 Previous scan

  • Marginal model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + acs_local + error
  • Interactgion model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + acs_local + acs_local:SmokCigNow + error

Reports

3.2 Current scan

Step (1) The baseline (liner-mixed) model before testing for local ancestry association:

  • Marginal model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + (1|ccenter) + (1|sid) + error
  • Interaction model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + (1|ccenter) + (1|sid) + (1|esid) + error

According to notation in (Sul et al. 2016):

  • Marginal model: \(var(y) = \sigma^2_c \Sigma_{centers} + \sigma^2_g K + \sigma^2_e I\)
  • Interaction model:
    • (marginal varcov) \(var(y) = \sigma^2_c \Sigma_{centers} + \sigma^2_g K + \sigma^2_e I\)
    • (interaction varcov) \(var(y) = \sigma^2_c \Sigma_{centers} + \sigma^2_g K + \sigma^2_{ge} K_d + \sigma^2_e I\)

Step (2) The association (weigthed linear) model, in which the variance-covariance matrix from model (1) is used.

  • Marginal model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + acs_global + weighted_error
  • Interaction model: FEV1_FVC_utah ~ ... + SmokCigNow + acs_global + acs_local + acs_global::SmokCigNow + acs_local:SmokCigNow + weighted_error

7 Additional material

7.1 Marginal scans in other phenotypes

We do not show all QQ-plots, but we have checked that the inflation was improved in certain ways by applying the LMM1 + GLS strategy. But there are still some issues on tails of low (significant) p-values. Possible reasons might be:

  • related statistics;
  • proximal contamination (\(K\) is estimated in all chromosomes).

8 TODO

  • Wait for results on marginal scans for all traits (current computations are still on-going).
  • Run interaction scans for LMMs that include both \(K\) and \(K_d\) (interaction varcov)
    • Here, we observed that LMMs with only \(K\) (marginal varcov) can not fix the inflation issue. That is consistent with results in (Sul et al. 2016).
  • Implement efficient computation of scans, so permutation test are feasible.
    • Take inspiration from (Shabalin 2012).
    • Modules:
      • Project out covariates
      • Estimate p-values by computing correlation matrices
      • Store large matrices efficiently (netcf4, hdf5, big.matrix)
      • Take into account interaction tests
  • Estimate permutation p-values for top signals
    • marginal signal in Chr 12
    • interaction signal in Chr 11
  • Include all rather than long ancestry segments
